==English==

===Noun===
'''Buggins' [[turn]]'''
#{{idiom}} The appointment of a person by [[rotation]] or [[promotion]], on the basis of length of [[service]] (it being that person's "[[turn]]") rather than [[merit]] or level of [[qualification]]. 
#: ''He will be appointed on the principle of '''Buggins' turn'''.''

===Etymology===
Earliest recorded use is by Admiral Fisher, later First Sea Lord, in a 1901 letter.  In a 1917 letter, reprinted in his ''Memories'' (1919), Fisher said "Some day the [[Empire]] will go down because it is Buggins' turn."